In mathematics, a **Voronoi diagram** is a partitioning of a plane into regions based on distance to points in a specific subset of the plane. That set of points (called seeds, sites, or generators) is specified beforehand, and for each seed there is a corresponding region consisting of all points closer to that seed than to any other. These regions are called Voronoi cells. The Voronoi diagram of a set of points is dual to its Delaunay triangulation.

The origin of Voronoi diagram dates back to the 17th century. R. Descartes claims in his book \[2\] that the solar system consists of vortices. This concept has independently emerged, and proven useful, in various fields of science.

The mathematicians Dirichlet and Voronoi were the first to formally introduce this concept. They used it for the study of quadratic forms.

The resulting structure has been called Dirichlet tessellation or Voronoi diagram, which has become its standard name today. The Voronoi diagram is the result of a simple interpolation method. The boundaries of the cells represent the locations that are equidistant from two or more seeds.

Consider S={s1, s2, ..., sn} as a set of distinct sites in space and d(si,) the Euclidean distance between two sites, and . We define the Voronoi region of a site in Definition 1. The Voronoi region of a site, V(si), of all the points whose nearest site is si:

> V(si)={x:d(si ,x)? d( ,x) , ? j!=i} .... (1)

The union of the Voronoi regions of all sites represents a tessellation of the space that is called Voronoi tessellation:

Note that some points do not have a unique nearest site. The set of all points that have more than one nearest site forms the Voronoi diagram. Figure 2 shows a Voronoi diagram of 11 points in the Euclidean plane.
